    amenType: 'Dr. Amen\'s Type 3: Over-Focused ADD. SPECT imaging reveals significant, chronic overactivity in the anterior cingulate gyrus (the brain\'s "gear shifter") combined with decreased prefrontal cortex activity. The gear shifter is stuck — the brain cannot shift from one thought to the next.',
    prevalence: 'Common among children and grandchildren of people who are or were addicted to alcohol or other substances. Frequently overlaps with OCD traits. Often missed because the "hyperfocus" is mistaken for diligence or determination.',
    mechanism: 'Anterior cingulate gyrus overactivity combined with prefrontal cortex underactivity. The anterior cingulate normally allows cognitive flexibility — shifting from thought to thought, adapting to change. When it is overactive, the brain gets stuck. Simultaneously, low serotonin levels impair the brain\'s ability to generate the neurochemical "release" needed to shift gears.',
    coreChallenge: 'Pathological hyper-focus and a devastating inability to shift cognitive gears. The brain locks onto negative thoughts, grudges, worries, or rigid behavioral patterns and cannot release them. This is ADD plus cognitive rigidity — a combination that is deeply misunderstood by those around them.',
