    attention: 'The opposite of scattered — locked on. Attention doesn\'t drift; it GRIPS. The person can spend hours thinking about a slight from three years ago, replaying a conversation, or unable to stop worrying about a future event. Interest-driven but inflexible.',
    sensory: 'Heightened sensitivity to perceived wrongness. Sensory issues may not be the primary feature, but environmental disruptions (things out of place, unexpected changes) trigger disproportionate cognitive loops.',
    emotional: 'Rigid emotional responses. Gets locked into anger, sadness, or worry and cannot self-modulate. Arguments become circular because the brain physically cannot "move on." Holds grudges for years — not by choice, but because the anterior cingulate won\'t release the grievance.',
    social: 'Argumentative and oppositional — not from malice but from neurological rigidity. Says "no" automatically before processing the request. Gets stuck on their position in disagreements. Relationships suffer from an inability to "agree to disagree."',
    work: 'Excels in environments requiring sustained focus on a single domain — quality control, editing, research, compliance. Struggles severely with shifting priorities, multi-project environments, or collaborative brainstorming that requires letting go of one\'s own ideas.',
    home: 'Rigid routines that serve both stability and inflexibility. May insist on specific ways of loading the dishwasher, organizing the pantry, or scheduling the week. Disruption to these systems causes disproportionate distress.',
    time: 'Distorted by perseveration. Can lose hours to a worry loop or argument replay and be genuinely surprised by how much time passed. Difficulty transitioning from one time block to the next.',
    reading: 'May re-read the same passage repeatedly trying to achieve "perfect" comprehension. Writing can be slow because of obsessive editing. Emails may be over-long as the brain tries to cover every possible interpretation.',
    masking: 'Moderate. The rigidity is visible to close contacts. May develop a reputation as "stubborn," "inflexible," or "argumentative" that they cannot shake despite effort.',
    selfAwareness: 'Low for the cognitive rigidity component. May recognize worry patterns but attribute them to anxiety disorder rather than an attention regulation issue. Often doesn\'t realize they\'re stuck until someone else points it out.',
    feedback: 'Deeply problematic. Feedback contradicts the brain\'s locked position, creating conflict rather than integration. May argue against feedback for hours, not because they disagree on content, but because the anterior cingulate can\'t release the original position.',
    whatMissed: 'That their "stubbornness" is neurological, not characterological. That their inability to let go of a thought, argument, or worry is as involuntary as ADHD-I\'s inability to sustain attention. That they are exhausted by their own loops but cannot stop them.',
