  'asd-1': {
    id: 'asd-1',
    name: 'ASD — Level 1',
    color: '#2DD4BF',
    colorClass: 'nt-asd1',
    icon: '/static/images/icons/asd-1.jpg',
    tagline: 'Deep precision in a world that rewards shallow speed — a brain built for expertise, not small talk.',
    prevalence: 'Estimated 1–2% of adults. Significantly underdiagnosed in high-masking individuals, women, and people of color. 50–70% of autistic individuals also meet ADHD criteria, but this profile describes autism without significant ADHD traits.',
    mechanism: 'Distributed cortical differences in orbitofrontal cortex, superior temporal sulcus, fusiform gyrus, and amygdala. Characterized by long-range underconnectivity with heightened local connectivity — the brain is wired for depth rather than breadth. Monotropism theory describes this as a "monotropic" attention system that channels resources into a single, deep attention tunnel rather than distributing attention broadly (polytropically). This explains both the extraordinary depth of special interests and the difficulty with task-switching.',
    coreChallenge: 'Social communication and sensory processing are the primary bottlenecks — NOT attention. The autistic brain navigates a world designed for neurotypical social intuition and sensory calibration. DSM-5-TR requires persistent deficits in ALL three: social-emotional reciprocity, nonverbal communication, and relationship building (Criterion A), PLUS at least TWO restricted/repetitive behaviors (Criterion B).',
    executiveFunction: 'Cognitive flexibility and set-shifting are primary deficits — affecting up to 80% of autistic individuals. Working memory for conversations and cognitive flexibility in novel situations are impaired, but planning can be superior in structured contexts. The "cool" executive functions (logic-based) are often stronger than "hot" executive functions (emotion-driven decisions).',
    attention: 'Monotropic attention: intense, deep, and inflexible. The brain channels resources into a single attention tunnel, creating extraordinary depth but difficulty disengaging. This explains "autistic inertia" — the intense difficulty of shifting focus once engaged. Enhanced visual search ability. Joint attention is specifically impaired.',
    sensory: 'The defining feature of the autistic experience. Structural brain connectivity differences create hyper-sensitivity (sensory overload from sounds, lights, textures), hypo-sensitivity (failure to register certain cues), or both. Interoception — the "eighth sense" monitoring internal body states — is often dysregulated. Approximately 50% experience alexithymia (difficulty identifying and naming emotions), rooted in interoceptive differences. Sensory overload triggers autonomic threat responses (meltdowns/shutdowns).',
    emotional: 'Alexithymia affects approximately 50% of autistic adults — difficulty identifying and naming emotions, rooted in interoceptive differences. This is the primary mechanism for anxiety crises and eating disorders in autistic individuals. Emotional responses may be delayed — processed hours or days later. Meltdowns and shutdowns are nervous system responses to overload, not "tantrums." Autistic burnout — a specific syndrome distinct from clinical depression — results from chronic masking and sensory overload, lasting months and requiring radical rest.',
    social: 'Challenges with pragmatic language, nonverbal cues, and reciprocal conversation. Camouflaging (masking) is quantified by the CAT-Q framework with three components: Compensation (strategic social scripts), Masking (suppressing autistic traits, forcing eye contact), and Assimilation (performing to fit in). Scores above 100 indicate heavy cognitive labor. Higher in females — often leading to late diagnosis. Gender differences: women and non-binary individuals often internalize symptoms, showing shutdowns and dissociation rather than externalized behaviors.',
    work: 'Consistent but highly context-dependent. Excels at deep, specialized work requiring sustained concentration. Struggles with ambiguity, shifting priorities, and office politics.',
    home: 'Routine-based but rigid. Disruption of systems causes disproportionate distress. Needs environmental predictability.',
    time: 'Linear and objective within routine. Transitions between activities are cognitively costly.',
    reading: 'Slow, deliberate, and precise. Some individuals are hyperlexic. May miss implied meaning in text. Prefers written instructions over verbal.',
    masking: 'Strategic and learned. CAT-Q research shows three components: Compensation (rule-based tricks), Masking (impression management), and Assimilation (blending). The cognitive load is enormous and cumulative — directly linked to autistic burnout, depression, and suicidality.',
    selfAwareness: 'Variable — often high if diagnosed. RAADS-R (80-item self-report) is a key adult assessment tool with four subscales: Social Relatedness, Sensory-Motor, Circumscribed Interests, and Language.',
    feedback: 'Domain-specific and rule-based. Accepts objective, specific feedback readily. Struggles with vague, emotionally charged critique.',
    whatMissed: 'The distinction between autistic burnout and clinical depression — burnout requires radical rest, not behavioral activation (which can actually harm a burnt-out autistic person). How much identity was constructed around masking.',
    prognosis: 'Steady upward mobility when environment fit is achieved. The autistic brain can outperform peers in specialized domains when given explicit expectations and sensory-appropriate conditions.',
    strength: 'Deep expertise, systematic reliability, and the courage to dissent. The monotropic attention system, when honored, produces mastery that polytropic attention cannot match.',
    needToHear: '"Your value is not determined by how well you perform \'normal.\' The world needs your depth, your precision, your refusal to accept \'good enough\' when excellence is possible. You are not broken — you are specialized."',
    dimensions: {}
  },
